A somewhat accessible introduction to Zero Knowledge Proofs

Zero Knowledge Proofs (ZKP) are not mathematically trivial. One might balk as to how mathematically dense it could be at times. This albeit terse document aims to hopefully ease this transition slightly.

There are several pure mathematics, mathematical statistics, and theoretical computer science prerequisites needed to understand ZKPs, much less code them. We give the bare minimum background prerequisites for each.

Pure Math

We first define the bare minimum mathematical background to understand Zero Knowledge Proofs (ZKP), by introducing the concept of Groups, Fields, Elliptic Curves, and Bilinear Pairs.

Pairings allow us to translate translate a hard problem from an elliptic curve group (like ECDLP) to a hard problem in a different kind of groupspecifically, a multiplicative group within a finite field (a classical discrete logarithm problem). The key part of this is the fact that its in enabling cryptographic constructions that were previously impossible or highly inefficient - something which ZKPs make use of. We can demonstrate this by translating from the computational Diffie-Hellman (CDH) to Decision Diffie-Hellman (DDH) scheme.

Comment: The difference between both variants of Diffie-Hellman schemes is the underlying purpose of each variant. The CDH variant is used to securely generate a symmetric cryptographic key over a public channel, while the DDH variant is used to determine if a candidate key is the correct secret key

In fact, ZKPs use pairings in a similar manner: bilinear pairings let provers encode algebraic/witness relations as group-exponent relations and let verifiers check those relations with a small number of pairing evaluations. If this doesnt make sense now, dont worry. All will become clear in time.
